sec.p:
Looking for the balance between accuracy and precision of diagnoses at meat inspection, another option could be to support the work of meat inspectors with new digital techniques and artificial intelligence. In particular, artificial intelligence can be used to analyze and process large amounts of data from various sources, such as image processing system, chemical sensors, and microbiological tests to identify patterns and anomalies in meat quality, classify carcasses, detect potential health hazards, and provide real-time feedback to inspectors (26, 27). As a matter of fact, such options are already under development, such for instance the use of artificial intelligence for automatic detection of abattoir lesion (ADAL | F4T Lab) (28), photo artificial intelligence identification of animals (Phaid | F4T Lab
) (29) and scanning animal tattoos on slaughter line for traceability (ReaDop | F4T Lab
) (30).
